com.camerontec.util.stats

Class Histogram

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.camerontec.util.stats.Histogram

  • public final class Histogram
extends Object
    Lightweight histogram implementation.

    This implementation does not allow intervals for which any part of the internal is < 0.

    This class is not thread safe.

      • Histogram

        public Histogram(long[] intervalUpperBounds)
        Constructor.
        Parameters:
        intervalUpperBounds - The upper bounds of each interval for which sample intervalFrequencies are to be maintained. Intervals are this defined to be [ intervalUpperBounds[i-1], intervalUpperBounds[i] ). Therefore the supplied upper bounds must be positive and monotonically increasing.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If the supplied upper bounds are not positive and monotonically increasing.

      • getIntervalUpperBounds

        public long[] getIntervalUpperBounds()
        Return the interval upper bounds.

        Note: This method returns a copy of the interval upper bounds so any changes made have no effect. Also, copying the interval upper bounds involves object creation so it is not advisable to call this method unless necessary.

        Returns:
        A copy of the interval upper bounds.

      • getNumIntervals

        public int getNumIntervals()
        Return the number of intervals in the histogram.
        Returns:
        Number of defined intervals in the histogram. Note that the histogram also automatically counts negative and out of range positive samples separately. Those special intervals are not included here.

        public long getIntervalUpperBoundAt(int index)

      • getIntervalUpperBoundForConfidence

        public long getIntervalUpperBoundForConfidence(double confidence)
        Get the interval upper bound for a given confidence of the sample population.
        Parameters:
        confidence - Required confidence that number of samples is below the returned upper bound. Must be ≥ 0 and ≤ 1.
        Returns:
        The interval upper bound or 0L if there is no corresponding upper bound in the histogram. If the number of samples above the highest upper bound is such that the required confidence cannot be reached even when all internals are considered then Long.MIN_VALUE is returned.

      • toCSVString

        public String toCSVString()
        Return a String representation intervals and frequencies suitable for importing and a spreadsheet for further analysis.

        The format (assuming interval bounds of 2, 4, 6 with a single sample in each) is: 

         Interval,Frequency
 <0,0
 0-2,1
 2-4,1
 4-6,1
 >=6,0
        Returns:
        A CSV style representation of histogram intervals and frequencies.
